{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HR7TdfuiiZpMZZTbwMK8Yk","type":"tool_result","content":"   340→**3d-i: Build Docker verify image**\n   341→\n   342→```bash\n   343→codeharness verify-env build 2>&1\n   344→```\n   345→\n   346→If this fails:\n   347→```\n   348→[FAIL] verify-env build failed: {error}\n   349→```\n   350→Leave story at `verifying`, go to Step 6. No fallback.\n   351→\n   352→**3d-ii: Start Docker container**\n   353→\n   354→```bash\n   355→docker run -d --name codeharness-verify --network host \\\n   356→  -e ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=\"$ANTHROPIC_API_KEY\" \\\n   357→  codeharness-verify sleep infinity\n   358→```\n   359→\n   360→`--network host` allows the container to reach OTEL Collector at `localhost:4318`, VictoriaLogs at `:9428`, VictoriaMetrics at `:8428`, and VictoriaTraces at `:16686`. The `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` env var enables the `claude` CLI inside the container for verifier sessions that need to spawn Claude subprocesses.\n   361→\n   362→If `docker run` fails, log `[FAIL] docker run failed: {error}`, leave story at `verifying`, and go to Step 6. No cleanup needed — the container never started.\n   363→\n   364→**3d-iii: Prepare clean workspace**\n   365→\n   366→```bash\n   367→codeharness verify-env prepare --story {story_key} 2>&1\n   368→```\n   369→\n   370→This creates `/tmp/codeharness-verify-{story_key}` with built artifacts, docs, and story file — but NO source code.\n   371→\n   372→If this fails, log `[FAIL] verify-env prepare failed: {error}`, leave story at `verifying`, and go to cleanup (step 3d-viii) then Step 6. The container is running and must be cleaned up.\n   373→\n   374→**3d-iv: Run verifier session**\n   375→\n   376→Build the verification prompt and spawn the verifier:\n   377→\n   378→1. Read the story content from `/tmp/codeharness-verify-{story_key}/story.md`\n   379→2. Read the prompt template from `src/templates/verify-prompt.ts` — use `verifyPromptTemplate()` with the story content, container name `codeharness-verify`, and default observability endpoints\n   380→3. Run the verifier:\n   381→\n   382→```bash\n   383→cd /tmp/codeharness-verify-{story_key} && claude --print --max-budget-usd 5 --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"{verification_prompt}\"\n   384→```\n   385→\n   386→The prompt (from `src/templates/verify-prompt.ts`) instructs the verifier that:\n   387→\n   388→- It has **NO source code access** — `src/` does not exist in the workspace\n   389→- **ALL CLI commands** must run via `docker exec codeharness-verify <command>`\n   390→- It should read `README.md` for usage guidance\n   391→- It should query observability endpoints from the host:\n   392→  - VictoriaLogs: `http://localhost:9428`\n   393→  - VictoriaMetrics: `http://localhost:8428`\n   394→  - VictoriaTraces: `http://localhost:16686`\n   395→- The proof document goes in `verification/{story_key}-proof.md` within the clean workspace\n   396→- REAL failures must be reported — never fabricate evidence\n   397→- ACs that cannot be verified should be marked `[ESCALATE]`\n   398→\n   399→If the verifier process exits non-zero or times out, treat as failure (proceed to retry logic in step 3d-vii).\n   400→\n   401→**3d-v: Copy proof document back**\n   402→\n   403→```bash\n   404→cp /tmp/codeharness-verify-{story_key}/verification/{story_key}-proof.md verification/\n   405→```\n   406→\n   407→If the proof file does not exist (verifier crashed or failed to produce one), treat as failure (step 3d-vii).\n   408→\n   409→**3d-vi: Validate proof quality**\n   410→\n   411→```bash\n   412→codeharness verify --story {story_key} 2>&1\n   413→```\n   414→\n   415→Parse the output/exit code. After parsing each AC verdict from the proof, update the live progress:\n   416→\n   417→```bash\n   418→codeharness progress --ac-progress \"{passed}/{total}\"\n   419→```\n   420→\n   421→where `passed` is ACs with PASS verdict and `total` is all ACs.\n   422→\n   423→- If `pending === 0` and `escalated === 0` → proof quality passed. Update sprint-status.yaml: change `{story_key}` status to `done`. Print: `[OK] Story {story_key}: verifying → done`. Proceed to cleanup (step 3d-viii).\n   424→- If `escalated > 0` and `pending === 0` → verifier could not reach some ACs. **Before accepting escalation, diagnose WHY:**\n   425→  1. Read the proof document. For each `[ESCALATE]` AC, check the reason.\n   426→  2. **If the reason is infrastructure/tooling** (container missing binary, tree-shaking, Docker not configured, wrong version installed): this is NOT a valid escalation. The infrastructure needs fixing. Treat as **Path C** below.\n   427→  3. **If the reason is genuinely impossible to automate** (requires physical hardware, paid external service, human visual judgment): accept the escalation. Print: `[WARN] Story {story_key} has {N} genuinely escalated ACs — marking done with known limitations`. Update status to `done`.\n   428→  4. **Do NOT leave stories at `verifying` with escalated ACs.** Either fix the infra problem (Path C) or accept and mark done.\n   429→- If `pending > 0` → proof has gaps. Treat as failure (step 3d-vii).\n   430→\n   431→If the verifier made code fixes (detected by checking `git diff` after verification), run:\n   432→```bash\n   433→npm run build && npm run test:unit\n   434→```\n   435→to confirm fixes haven't broken anything. Then proceed to cleanup (step 3d-viii).\n   436→\n   437→**3d-vii: Failure handling — code bugs vs infrastructure failures**\n   438→\n   439→Determine the failure type. There are two distinct paths:"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017T6a4hLkrgVbCgAqvDRzfv","session_id":"f9b706e3-1764-4868-a4a5-c90b37d26d0d","uuid":"cef4a5e5-e72d-4afc-934e-070fb260cf45","timestamp":"2026-03-27T12:00:13.077Z"}
