{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DwHynniyDy4roeg1rACQcj","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→description: Start autonomous execution — run one sprint in the current session, iterating through stories using BMAD workflows.\n     3→---\n     4→\n     5→# Harness Run — In-Session Sprint Execution\n     6→\n     7→Execute stories autonomously in the current Claude Code session. Reads sprint-status.yaml, iterates through stories using BMAD workflows (create-story → dev-story → code-review → verify), and updates status after each story. This is the single source of sprint execution logic.\n     8→\n     9→> **MANDATORY — Never skip or shortcut verification.**\n    10→> Process stories one at a time, in order. Verification (Step 3d) is the entire point of codeharness — it catches real bugs. If there are 50 stories at `verifying`, verify them one by one. Each verification may surface issues that need fixing — that is the job. Never ask the user to batch-transition statuses, never propose \"lighter\" verification, never skip showboat proofs. If context window is a concern, that is why Ralph loop exists — each session handles a few stories, then a fresh session continues. Do not question, negotiate, or offer alternatives to the process defined below.\n    11→\n    12→## Step 1: Pre-flight — Read Sprint Status\n    13→\n    14→Read the sprint status file to understand current state.\n    15→\n    16→1. Read `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml` in full.\n    17→2. Parse the `development_status` section. Each entry is one of:\n    18→   - **Epic entry:** key matching `epic-N` (e.g., `epic-1`) — status is `backlog`, `in-progress`, or `done`\n    19→   - **Story entry:** key matching `N-M-slug` (e.g., `1-2-user-auth`) — status is `backlog`, `ready-for-dev`, `in-progress`, `review`, `verifying`, or `done`\n    20→   - **Retrospective entry:** key matching `epic-N-retrospective` — status is `optional` or `done`\n    21→3. If the file doesn't exist or has no `development_status`, HALT:\n    22→   ```\n    23→   [FAIL] No sprint-status.yaml found. Run /sprint-planning first.\n    24→   ```\n    25→\n    26→Initialize tracking variables (once, before the loop):\n    27→- `stories_completed = 0`\n    28→- `stories_failed = 0`\n    29→- `stories_skipped = 0`\n    30→- `skipped_reasons = []` (list of `{story_key}: {reason}` strings)\n    31→- `attempts = 0` (per story, resets for each new story — counts ALL retries: dev failures, review round-trips, verify→dev loops)\n    32→- `max_attempts = 10` (single limit for all retry types)\n    33→- `start_time = current timestamp`\n    34→\n    35→## Step 2: Find Next Actionable Story (Cross-Epic Scan)\n    36→\n    37→Scan ALL stories across ALL epics to find the highest-priority actionable story. Epic boundaries do not constrain selection.\n    38→\n    39→1. **Collect all stories:** Gather every `N-M-slug` entry from `development_status`, regardless of which epic it belongs to.\n    40→\n    41→2. **Filter out non-actionable stories.** Remove any story that matches ANY of these conditions:\n    42→   - Status is `done`\n    43→   - **Retry-exhausted:** Read `ralph/.story_retries`. If a line `{story_key}={count}` exists and `count >= max_attempts` (10), the story is retry-exhausted. Increment `stories_skipped`, append `{story_key}: retry-exhausted ({count}/{max_attempts})` to `skipped_reasons`, and print:\n    44→     ```\n    45→     [INFO] Skipping {story_key}: retry-exhausted ({count}/{max_attempts})\n    46→     ```\n    47→   - **Blocked (escalated):** A `verifying` story that already has a proof document (`verification/{story_key}-proof.md` exists) with `escalated > 0` and `pending === 0` is blocked. Increment `stories_skipped`, append `{story_key}: blocked (escalated ACs)` to `skipped_reasons`, and print:\n    48→     ```\n    49→     [INFO] Skipping {story_key}: blocked (escalated ACs)\n    50→     ```\n    51→\n    52→3. **Prioritize remaining stories.** Sort actionable stories into priority tiers (process highest tier first, file order within each tier):\n    53→   - **Tier A — Proof exists, needs validation:** Status is `verifying` AND `verification/{story_key}-proof.md` exists (but story is not blocked per step 2). These are quick wins — just need validation.\n    54→   - **Tier B — In-progress or review:** Status is `in-progress` or `review`. Resume partially-completed work.\n    55→   - **Tier C — Verifying without proof:** Status is `verifying` AND no proof document exists. Needs full Docker verification.\n    56→   - **Tier D — Backlog/ready-for-dev:** Status is `backlog` or `ready-for-dev`. New work.\n    57→\n    58→4. **Select the first story from the prioritized list.** If the list is empty (no actionable stories remain anywhere), go to Step 7 with result `NO_WORK`.\n    59→\n    60→5. **Determine the story's parent epic** (epic number N from the story key `N-M-slug`).\n    61→\n    62→6. **Reset per-story counter:** Set `attempts = 0` for the new story. (Note: if the story has persisted retry state in `ralph/.story_retries` that is below `max_attempts`, read that count and set `attempts` accordingly — this ensures retry budgets persist across sessions.)\n    63→\n    64→7. Print the plan:\n    65→   ```\n    66→   [INFO] Next story: {story_key} (status: {current_status}, tier: {A|B|C|D})\n    67→   [INFO] Parent epic: Epic {N}\n    68→   [INFO] Stories in epic: {done_count}/{total_count} done\n    69→   ```\n    70→\n    71→## Subagent Mandatory Report Sections\n    72→\n    73→Every subagent (create-story, dev-story, code-review, verifier, retrospective) MUST end its response with TWO sections:\n    74→\n    75→### 1. Session Issues\n    76→\n    77→A `## Session Issues` section reporting problems, workarounds, suboptimal outcomes, and observations — not just success/failure status.\n    78→\n    79→### 2. Token Usage Report\n    80→\n    81→A `## Token Report` section with tool call breakdown for cost analysis:\n    82→\n    83→```markdown\n    84→## Token Report\n    85→- Total tool calls: N\n    86→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, Glob: U, Agent: T\n    87→- Largest Bash outputs: \"{command}\" (~N lines), \"{command}\" (~N lines)\n    88→- Files read: N unique files, M total read calls (list files read 3+ times)\n    89→- Redundant operations: {describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or unnecessary calls}\n    90→```\n    91→\n    92→**After each subagent returns**, extract BOTH sections and append to the session issues log file at `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/.session-issues.md`. Use the following format:\n    93→\n    94→```markdown\n    95→### {story_key} — {step name} ({timestamp})\n    96→\n    97→{extracted issues from subagent response}\n    98→\n    99→{extracted token report from subagent response}\n   100→```\n   101→\n   102→If the subagent didn't include a Session Issues section, append:\n   103→```markdown\n   104→### {story_key} — {step name} ({timestamp})\n   105→\n   106→No issues reported (subagent did not include Session Issues section — this itself is an issue).\n   107→```\n   108→\n   109→Initialize the issues file at the start of the session (Step 1) by writing a header:\n   110→```markdown\n   111→# Session Issues Log — {date}\n   112→```\n   113→\n   114→## Step 3: Execute Story Lifecycle\n   115→\n   116→Based on the story's current status, determine which workflow(s) to run. Execute them in sequence, verifying status transitions after each.\n   117→\n   118→> **TOKEN OPTIMIZATION — Use Subagents for Heavy Commands**\n   119→>\n   120→> The parent orchestrator's conversation context grows with every tool call. Large outputs (build logs, test results, coverage reports) snowball the context and make every subsequent API call expensive.\n   121→>\n   122→> **Rule: Any command that produces >50 lines of output should run inside a subagent.**\n   123→>\n   124→> The subagent sees the full output, processes it, and returns a ONE-LINE summary to the parent. This keeps the parent context small.\n   125→>\n   126→> Apply this to: `cargo build`, `cargo test`, `cargo clippy`, `cargo tarpaulin`, `npm test`, `npm run build`, `docker build`, `codeharness verify --story`, and any other verbose command.\n   127→>\n   128→> **Pattern:**\n   129→> ```\n   130→> Use the Agent tool with:\n   131→>   prompt: \"Run `{command}` in {directory}. Report result as a single line:\n   132→>   PASS — {summary} OR FAIL — {first 5 error lines}\"\n   133→>   subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   134→> ```\n   135→>\n   136→> **Do NOT run these commands directly with Bash from the parent orchestrator.** The subagent absorbs the output; the parent stays lean.\n   137→>\n   138→> **Also avoid redundant calls:**\n   139→> - Read sprint-status.yaml ONCE at session start (Step 1), not per-story\n   140→> - `codeharness progress --clear` ONCE per story, not twice\n   141→> - Timestamps: use the current time from your system prompt, don't shell out to `date`\n   142→> - Don't re-read files that haven't changed since last read\n   143→\n   144→**Live progress updates:** Before executing each sub-step (3a/3b/3c/3d), update sprint-state.json with the current progress:\n   145→\n   146→```bash\n   147→codeharness progress --story {story_key} --phase {create|dev|review|verify} --action \"Starting {step description}\"\n   148→```\n   149→\n   150→This enables external tools to see what the session is doing in real time.\n   151→\n   152→### 3a: If status is `backlog` — Run Create Story\n   153→\n   154→Invoke the create-story workflow via Agent tool to generate the story file:\n   155→\n   156→```\n   157→Use the Agent tool with:\n   158→  prompt: \"Run /create-story for story {story_key}. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append `<!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->` or `<!-- verification: integration-required -->` based on whether the AC can be verified by running CLI commands in a subprocess. ACs referencing workflows, sprint planning, user sessions, or external system interactions should be tagged as integration-required. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n   159→\n   160→MANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n   161→- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n   162→- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n   163→- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n   164→- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\n   165→If nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n   166→\n   167→MANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n   168→- Total tool calls: N\n   169→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n   170→- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n   171→- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n   172→- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls\"\n   173→  subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   174→```\n   175→\n   176→After the Agent completes:\n   177→1. Re-read `sprint-status.yaml`\n   178→2. Verify the story status changed from `backlog` to `ready-for-dev`\n   179→3. If status didn't change, increment attempts and retry this step (up to max_attempts)\n   180→4. Print: `[OK] Story {story_key}: backlog → ready-for-dev`\n   181→\n   182→### 3b: If status is `ready-for-dev` or `in-progress` — Run Dev Story\n   183→\n   184→**Pre-check: Verification findings.** Before invoking dev-story, read the story file at `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md` and check if it contains a `## Verification Findings` section. If it does, extract the full content of that section (everything from `## Verification Findings` until the next `##` heading or end of file). Store this as `verification_findings_text`.\n   185→\n   186→Invoke the dev-story workflow via Agent tool to implement the story:\n   187→\n   188→```\n   189→Use the Agent tool with:\n   190→  prompt: \"Run /bmad-dev-story for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md — implement all tasks, write tests, and mark the story for review. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously through all tasks until complete. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n   191→\n   192→{IF verification_findings_text is not empty, include this block:}\n   193→IMPORTANT — VERIFICATION FINDINGS FROM PREVIOUS CYCLE:\n   194→The following ACs failed verification. Fix the code to make them pass:\n   195→\n   196→{verification_findings_text}\n   197→\n   198→Read the findings carefully. Each failing AC includes the error output from the verifier. Your job is to fix the underlying code so these ACs pass on the next verification run. Do NOT remove the ## Verification Findings section from the story file — it stays for reference.\n   199→{END IF block}\n   200→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01WTx8j9hk9cZfjCVrJFg5MD","session_id":"f9b706e3-1764-4868-a4a5-c90b37d26d0d","uuid":"44aa326d-2956-4a42-8933-a818f16c2439","timestamp":"2026-03-27T12:03:48.501Z"}
