{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Kf8dWDo1ajNqYCtvjWb5u8","type":"tool_result","content":"   200→\n   201→MANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n   202→- Problems encountered (build failures, test failures, unclear task specs, missing APIs)\n   203→- Workarounds applied (anything hacky, copied patterns that felt wrong, TODOs left behind)\n   204→- Code quality concerns (areas that need refactoring, edge cases not handled, tech debt added)\n   205→- Observations (unexpected complexity, architectural mismatches, dependency issues)\n   206→If nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n   207→\n   208→MANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n   209→- Total tool calls: N\n   210→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n   211→- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n   212→- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n   213→- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls\"\n   214→  subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   215→```\n   216→\n   217→After the Agent completes:\n   218→1. Re-read `sprint-status.yaml`\n   219→2. Verify the story status changed to `review`\n   220→3. If status is still `in-progress` or `ready-for-dev`, this may indicate failure — increment attempts\n   221→4. If attempts >= max_attempts, go to Step 6 (failure handling)\n   222→5. If status didn't reach `review`, retry this step\n   223→6. Print: `[OK] Story {story_key}: → review`\n   224→\n   225→### 3c: If status is `review` — Run Code Review\n   226→\n   227→Invoke the code-review workflow via Agent tool:\n   228→\n   229→```\n   230→Use the Agent tool with:\n   231→  prompt: \"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n   232→\n   233→MANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n   234→- Bugs found and their severity (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW with brief description)\n   235→- Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt)\n   236→- Coverage gaps (files below floor, untested edge cases, areas needing integration tests)\n   237→- Architecture concerns (patterns that don't fit, coupling issues, missing abstractions)\n   238→- Items sent back for re-development (what failed and why)\n   239→If nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n   240→\n   241→MANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n   242→- Total tool calls: N\n   243→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n   244→- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n   245→- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n   246→- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls\"\n   247→  subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   248→```\n   249→\n   250→After the Agent completes:\n   251→1. Re-read `sprint-status.yaml`\n   252→2. Check the story status:\n   253→   - If `verifying` → Code review passed and coverage verified. Print `[OK] Story {story_key}: review → verifying`. Go to Step 3d.\n   254→   - If `in-progress` → Code review found issues and sent story back for fixes. Increment `attempts`. If `attempts >= max_attempts`, go to Step 6 (failure). Print `[WARN] Story {story_key}: review → in-progress (issues found, re-developing, attempt {attempts}/{max_attempts})`. Go to Step 3b to re-run dev-story.\n   255→   - If still `review` → Code review may have failed silently. Increment attempts. If attempts >= max_attempts, go to Step 6. Otherwise retry this step.\n   256→\n   257→### 3d: If status is `verifying` — Run Verification\n   258→\n   259→> **CRITICAL — CHECK VERIFICATION TIER FIRST. DO NOT SKIP THIS CHECK.**\n   260→\n   261→**Step 3d-0: Read the story file and check for verification tier tag.**\n   262→\n   263→Read `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md`. Search for `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->` anywhere in the file.\n   264→\n   265→- **If the tag `<!-- verification-tier: unit-testable -->` IS found:** Use **unit-testable verification** (below). Do NOT use Docker. Do NOT run `codeharness stack start`. Do NOT build Docker images. Do NOT start containers. Go directly to the unit-testable verification flow.\n   266→- **If the tag is NOT found:** Use **black-box verification** (default, with Docker).\n   267→\n   268→**Unit-testable verification (when tagged):**\n   269→\n   270→Use a **single subagent** for the entire verification. This keeps build/test output out of the parent context (saves ~80% of verification tokens).\n   271→\n   272→```\n   273→Use the Agent tool with:\n   274→  prompt: \"Verify story {story_key} using local CLI checks (unit-testable tier).\n   275→\n   276→Story file: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md\n   277→\n   278→Execute these steps and report results:\n   279→1. Run the project build command (npm run build, cargo build, etc). Report: PASS or FAIL + first 10 error lines.\n   280→2. Run tests (npm test, cargo test, etc). Report: PASS (N passed) or FAIL (N failed: list names).\n   281→3. Run linter if configured (cargo clippy, eslint, etc). Report: PASS or FAIL + warning count.\n   282→4. Run coverage if configured (cargo tarpaulin, vitest --coverage, etc). Report: coverage percentage.\n   283→5. For each AC in the story file, verify it:\n   284→   - File existence: ls path/to/file\n   285→   - Exports: grep 'export' path/to/file\n   286→   - Function existence: grep 'function name' path/to/file\n   287→   - Test output: check relevant test names in output\n   288→   Report each AC as PASS or FAIL with one-line evidence.\n   289→6. Generate proof document at verification/{story_key}-proof.md with evidence from each check.\n   290→7. Run codeharness verify --story {story_key} to validate the proof format.\n   291→8. Report final result: ALL_PASS (N/N ACs) or PARTIAL (M/N ACs, list failures).\n   292→\n   293→Do NOT ask the user any questions. Do NOT run git commands. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n   294→\n   295→MANDATORY — End your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n   296→- Total tool calls: N\n   297→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n   298→- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n   299→- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n   300→- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls\"\n   301→  subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   302→```\n   303→\n   304→After the subagent returns:\n   305→1. Extract the `## Token Report` section and append to `.session-issues.md`\n   306→2. Parse the result: ALL_PASS → mark story `done`. PARTIAL → treat as failure (Step 3d-vii Path A).\n   307→2. **No Docker involved at any point.** Skip steps 3d-i through 3d-viii entirely.\n   308→\n   309→**Black-box verification (default, no tag):** Full Docker container with no source code access.\n   310→\n   311→**No internal timeout.** Verification takes as long as it takes. Ralph's iteration timeout is the safety net.\n   312→\n   313→**Pre-verification: Read retry state from `ralph/.story_retries`.**\n   314→\n   315→Read the file `ralph/.story_retries`. If the file contains a line matching `{story_key}={N}`, set `attempts = N`. If no matching line exists, set `attempts = 0`. This ensures retry budgets persist across sessions.\n   316→\n   317→**Pre-verification: Check observability infrastructure.**\n   318→\n   319→```bash\n   320→codeharness status --check-docker 2>&1\n   321→```\n   322→\n   323→If the output indicates the observability stack is down:\n   324→```bash\n   325→codeharness stack start 2>&1\n   326→```\n   327→\n   328→If `codeharness stack start` fails, log `[FAIL] Observability stack failed to start — cannot verify` and go to Step 6 (failure handling).\n   329→\n   330→**Pre-verification: Build dist/.**\n   331→\n   332→```bash\n   333→npm run build 2>&1\n   334→```\n   335→\n   336→If the build fails, fix errors before proceeding. The Docker image needs current dist/.\n   337→\n   338→**Verification flow — execute these steps sequentially:**\n   339→\n   340→**3d-i: Build Docker verify image**\n   341→\n   342→```bash\n   343→codeharness verify-env build 2>&1\n   344→```\n   345→\n   346→If this fails:\n   347→```\n   348→[FAIL] verify-env build failed: {error}\n   349→```\n   350→Leave story at `verifying`, go to Step 6. No fallback.\n   351→\n   352→**3d-ii: Start Docker container**\n   353→\n   354→```bash\n   355→docker run -d --name codeharness-verify --network host \\\n   356→  -e ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=\"$ANTHROPIC_API_KEY\" \\\n   357→  codeharness-verify sleep infinity\n   358→```\n   359→\n   360→`--network host` allows the container to reach OTEL Collector at `localhost:4318`, VictoriaLogs at `:9428`, VictoriaMetrics at `:8428`, and VictoriaTraces at `:16686`. The `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` env var enables the `claude` CLI inside the container for verifier sessions that need to spawn Claude subprocesses.\n   361→\n   362→If `docker run` fails, log `[FAIL] docker run failed: {error}`, leave story at `verifying`, and go to Step 6. No cleanup needed — the container never started.\n   363→\n   364→**3d-iii: Prepare clean workspace**\n   365→\n   366→```bash\n   367→codeharness verify-env prepare --story {story_key} 2>&1\n   368→```\n   369→\n   370→This creates `/tmp/codeharness-verify-{story_key}` with built artifacts, docs, and story file — but NO source code.\n   371→\n   372→If this fails, log `[FAIL] verify-env prepare failed: {error}`, leave story at `verifying`, and go to cleanup (step 3d-viii) then Step 6. The container is running and must be cleaned up.\n   373→\n   374→**3d-iv: Run verifier session**\n   375→\n   376→Build the verification prompt and spawn the verifier:\n   377→\n   378→1. Read the story content from `/tmp/codeharness-verify-{story_key}/story.md`\n   379→2. Read the prompt template from `src/templates/verify-prompt.ts` — use `verifyPromptTemplate()` with the story content, container name `codeharness-verify`, and default observability endpoints\n   380→3. Run the verifier:\n   381→\n   382→```bash\n   383→cd /tmp/codeharness-verify-{story_key} && claude --print --max-budget-usd 5 --allowedTools Bash Read Write Glob Grep Edit -p \"{verification_prompt}\"\n   384→```\n   385→\n   386→The prompt (from `src/templates/verify-prompt.ts`) instructs the verifier that:\n   387→\n   388→- It has **NO source code access** — `src/` does not exist in the workspace\n   389→- **ALL CLI commands** must run via `docker exec codeharness-verify <command>`\n   390→- It should read `README.md` for usage guidance\n   391→- It should query observability endpoints from the host:\n   392→  - VictoriaLogs: `http://localhost:9428`\n   393→  - VictoriaMetrics: `http://localhost:8428`\n   394→  - VictoriaTraces: `http://localhost:16686`\n   395→- The proof document goes in `verification/{story_key}-proof.md` within the clean workspace\n   396→- REAL failures must be reported — never fabricate evidence\n   397→- ACs that cannot be verified should be marked `[ESCALATE]`\n   398→\n   399→If the verifier process exits non-zero or times out, treat as failure (proceed to retry logic in step 3d-vii).\n   400→\n   401→**3d-v: Copy proof document back**\n   402→\n   403→```bash\n   404→cp /tmp/codeharness-verify-{story_key}/verification/{story_key}-proof.md verification/\n   405→```\n   406→\n   407→If the proof file does not exist (verifier crashed or failed to produce one), treat as failure (step 3d-vii).\n   408→\n   409→**3d-vi: Validate proof quality**\n   410→\n   411→```bash\n   412→codeharness verify --story {story_key} 2>&1\n   413→```\n   414→\n   415→Parse the output/exit code. After parsing each AC verdict from the proof, update the live progress:\n   416→\n   417→```bash\n   418→codeharness progress --ac-progress \"{passed}/{total}\"\n   419→```\n   420→\n   421→where `passed` is ACs with PASS verdict and `total` is all ACs.\n   422→\n   423→- If `pending === 0` and `escalated === 0` → proof quality passed. Update sprint-status.yaml: change `{story_key}` status to `done`. Print: `[OK] Story {story_key}: verifying → done`. Proceed to cleanup (step 3d-viii).\n   424→- If `escalated > 0` and `pending === 0` → verifier could not reach some ACs. **Before accepting escalation, diagnose WHY:**\n   425→  1. Read the proof document. For each `[ESCALATE]` AC, check the reason.\n   426→  2. **If the reason is infrastructure/tooling** (container missing binary, tree-shaking, Docker not configured, wrong version installed): this is NOT a valid escalation. The infrastructure needs fixing. Treat as **Path C** below.\n   427→  3. **If the reason is genuinely impossible to automate** (requires physical hardware, paid external service, human visual judgment): accept the escalation. Print: `[WARN] Story {story_key} has {N} genuinely escalated ACs — marking done with known limitations`. Update status to `done`.\n   428→  4. **Do NOT leave stories at `verifying` with escalated ACs.** Either fix the infra problem (Path C) or accept and mark done.\n   429→- If `pending > 0` → proof has gaps. Treat as failure (step 3d-vii).\n   430→\n   431→If the verifier made code fixes (detected by checking `git diff` after verification), run:\n   432→```bash\n   433→npm run build && npm run test:unit\n   434→```\n   435→to confirm fixes haven't broken anything. Then proceed to cleanup (step 3d-viii).\n   436→\n   437→**3d-vii: Failure handling — code bugs vs infrastructure failures**\n   438→\n   439→Determine the failure type. There are two distinct paths:\n   440→\n   441→**Path A — Code bugs (`pending > 0` in proof validation):**\n   442→\n   443→A proof document exists and `codeharness verify` reported `pending > 0`. This means the feature has real bugs — the code does not satisfy the ACs. Code bugs NEVER count against the retry budget.\n   444→\n   445→1. **Extract failing ACs from the proof document.** Read `verification/{story_key}-proof.md`. For each AC section (`## AC N: description`), check if the verdict is not PASS and not `[ESCALATE]`. For each failing AC, extract:\n   446→   - The AC number and description (from the `## AC N:` heading)\n   447→   - The error output (from the `output` code blocks and any verdict text)\n   448→\n   449→2. **Save findings to the story file.** Read `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md`. If it already has a `## Verification Findings` section, replace that section entirely with the new findings. If not, append a new `## Verification Findings` section before the `## Dev Agent Record` section (or at the end if that section doesn't exist). Format:"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01WTx8j9hk9cZfjCVrJFg5MD","session_id":"f9b706e3-1764-4868-a4a5-c90b37d26d0d","uuid":"18989164-d0d7-4b71-88f4-3492fd5b60f4","timestamp":"2026-03-27T12:03:53.111Z"}
