{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GozV3P7SX63aHqNnkULPcx","type":"tool_result","content":"   200→{IF verification_findings_text is not empty, include this block:}\n   201→IMPORTANT — VERIFICATION FINDINGS FROM PREVIOUS CYCLE:\n   202→The following ACs failed verification. Fix the code to make them pass:\n   203→\n   204→{verification_findings_text}\n   205→\n   206→Read the findings carefully. Each failing AC includes the error output from the verifier. Your job is to fix the underlying code so these ACs pass on the next verification run. Do NOT remove the ## Verification Findings section from the story file — it stays for reference.\n   207→{END IF block}\n   208→\n   209→MANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n   210→- Problems encountered (build failures, test failures, unclear task specs, missing APIs)\n   211→- Workarounds applied (anything hacky, copied patterns that felt wrong, TODOs left behind)\n   212→- Code quality concerns (areas that need refactoring, edge cases not handled, tech debt added)\n   213→- Observations (unexpected complexity, architectural mismatches, dependency issues)\n   214→If nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n   215→\n   216→MANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n   217→- Total tool calls: N\n   218→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n   219→- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n   220→- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n   221→- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls\"\n   222→  subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   223→```\n   224→\n   225→After the Agent completes:\n   226→1. Re-read `sprint-status.yaml`\n   227→2. Verify the story status changed to `review`\n   228→3. If status is still `in-progress` or `ready-for-dev`, this may indicate failure — increment attempts\n   229→4. If attempts >= max_attempts, go to Step 6 (failure handling)\n   230→5. If status didn't reach `review`, retry this step\n   231→6. Print: `[OK] Story {story_key}: → review`\n   232→\n   233→### 3c: If status is `review` — Run Code Review\n   234→\n   235→Invoke the code-review workflow via Agent tool:\n   236→\n   237→```\n   238→Use the Agent tool with:\n   239→  prompt: \"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n   240→\n   241→MANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n   242→- Bugs found and their severity (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW with brief description)\n   243→- Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt)\n   244→- Coverage gaps (files below floor, untested edge cases, areas needing integration tests)\n   245→- Architecture concerns (patterns that don't fit, coupling issues, missing abstractions)\n   246→- Items sent back for re-development (what failed and why)\n   247→If nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n   248→\n   249→MANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n   250→- Total tool calls: N\n   251→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n   252→- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n   253→- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n   254→- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls\"\n   255→  subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   256→```\n   257→\n   258→After the Agent completes:\n   259→1. Re-read `sprint-status.yaml`\n   260→2. Check the story status:\n   261→   - If `verifying` → Code review passed and coverage verified. Print `[OK] Story {story_key}: review → verifying`. Go to Step 3d.\n   262→   - If `in-progress` → Code review found issues and sent story back for fixes. Increment `attempts`. If `attempts >= max_attempts`, go to Step 6 (failure). Print `[WARN] Story {story_key}: review → in-progress (issues found, re-developing, attempt {attempts}/{max_attempts})`. Go to Step 3b to re-run dev-story.\n   263→   - If still `review` → Code review may have failed silently. Increment attempts. If attempts >= max_attempts, go to Step 6. Otherwise retry this step.\n   264→\n   265→### 3d: If status is `verifying` — Run Verification\n   266→\n   267→> **CRITICAL — DERIVE VERIFICATION TIER BEFORE DISPATCHING. DO NOT SKIP THIS STEP.**\n   268→\n   269→**Step 3d-0: Read the story file and derive the verification tier from AC-level tags.**\n   270→\n   271→Read `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md`.\n   272→\n   273→**Ignore the story-level `<!-- verification-tier: ... -->` tag** (if present). It is NOT used for dispatch. AC-level tags are the sole source of truth.\n   274→\n   275→Parse ALL lines in the Acceptance Criteria section. For each AC, extract its `<!-- verification: {tier} -->` tag (if present). Map any legacy tag values via `LEGACY_TIER_MAP`: `cli-verifiable` → `test-provable`, `integration-required` → `environment-provable`, `unit-testable` → `test-provable`, `black-box` → `environment-provable`. Collect all parsed tiers into an array.\n   276→\n   277→Compute the story's derived tier: `maxTier(collectedTiers)`. If no AC-level tags are found at all, default to `test-provable`.\n   278→\n   279→Dispatch based on the derived tier:\n   280→- **`test-provable`** → Use **test-provable verification** (below). No Docker, no running the app.\n   281→- **`runtime-provable`** → Use **runtime-provable verification** (below). Build and run the app locally — no Docker stack.\n   282→- **`environment-provable`** → Use **environment-provable verification** (below). Full Docker flow.\n   283→- **`escalate`** → Use **escalate verification** (below). Mixed-tier dispatch per AC.\n   284→\n   285→**test-provable verification (derived tier = test-provable):**\n   286→\n   287→Use a **single subagent** for the entire verification. This keeps build/test output out of the parent context (saves ~80% of verification tokens).\n   288→\n   289→```\n   290→Use the Agent tool with:\n   291→  prompt: \"Verify story {story_key} using local CLI checks (test-provable tier).\n   292→\n   293→Story file: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md\n   294→\n   295→Execute these steps and report results:\n   296→1. Run the project build command (npm run build, cargo build, etc). Report: PASS or FAIL + first 10 error lines.\n   297→2. Run tests (npm test, cargo test, etc). Report: PASS (N passed) or FAIL (N failed: list names).\n   298→3. Run linter if configured (cargo clippy, eslint, etc). Report: PASS or FAIL + warning count.\n   299→4. Run coverage if configured (cargo tarpaulin, vitest --coverage, etc). Report: coverage percentage."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0116QeEpK9QPXZrqFgqyf1PK","session_id":"f9b706e3-1764-4868-a4a5-c90b37d26d0d","uuid":"a05461e2-d3db-4c9a-96de-554894f804c5","timestamp":"2026-03-27T12:11:53.172Z"}
