{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01P3MouU1sbq3rnUNR8chzQ2","type":"tool_result","content":"   268→\n   269→**Step 3d-0: Read the story file and derive the verification tier from AC-level tags.**\n   270→\n   271→Read `_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md`.\n   272→\n   273→**Ignore the story-level `<!-- verification-tier: ... -->` tag** (if present). It is NOT used for dispatch. AC-level tags are the sole source of truth.\n   274→\n   275→Parse ALL lines in the Acceptance Criteria section. For each AC, extract its `<!-- verification: {tier} -->` tag (if present). Map any legacy tag values via `LEGACY_TIER_MAP`: `cli-verifiable` → `test-provable`, `integration-required` → `environment-provable`, `unit-testable` → `test-provable`, `black-box` → `environment-provable`. Collect all parsed tiers into an array.\n   276→\n   277→Compute the story's derived tier: `maxTier(collectedTiers)`. If no AC-level tags are found at all, default to `test-provable`.\n   278→\n   279→Dispatch based on the derived tier:\n   280→- **`test-provable`** → Use **test-provable verification** (below). No Docker, no running the app.\n   281→- **`runtime-provable`** → Use **runtime-provable verification** (below). Build and run the app locally — no Docker stack.\n   282→- **`environment-provable`** → Use **environment-provable verification** (below). Full Docker flow.\n   283→- **`escalate`** → Use **escalate verification** (below). Mixed-tier dispatch per AC.\n   284→\n   285→**test-provable verification (derived tier = test-provable):**\n   286→\n   287→Use a **single subagent** for the entire verification. This keeps build/test output out of the parent context (saves ~80% of verification tokens).\n   288→\n   289→```\n   290→Use the Agent tool with:\n   291→  prompt: \"Verify story {story_key} using local CLI checks (test-provable tier).\n   292→\n   293→Story file: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md\n   294→\n   295→Execute these steps and report results:\n   296→1. Run the project build command (npm run build, cargo build, etc). Report: PASS or FAIL + first 10 error lines.\n   297→2. Run tests (npm test, cargo test, etc). Report: PASS (N passed) or FAIL (N failed: list names).\n   298→3. Run linter if configured (cargo clippy, eslint, etc). Report: PASS or FAIL + warning count.\n   299→4. Run coverage if configured (cargo tarpaulin, vitest --coverage, etc). Report: coverage percentage.\n   300→5. For each AC in the story file, verify it:\n   301→   - File existence: ls path/to/file\n   302→   - Exports: grep 'export' path/to/file\n   303→   - Function existence: grep 'function name' path/to/file\n   304→   - Test output: check relevant test names in output\n   305→   Report each AC as PASS or FAIL with one-line evidence.\n   306→6. Generate proof document at verification/{story_key}-proof.md with evidence from each check.\n   307→7. Run codeharness verify --story {story_key} to validate the proof format.\n   308→8. Report final result: ALL_PASS (N/N ACs) or PARTIAL (M/N ACs, list failures).\n   309→\n   310→Do NOT ask the user any questions. Do NOT run git commands. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n   311→\n   312→MANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n   313→- Problems encountered (build failures, test failures, missing files, unexpected behavior)\n   314→- Workarounds applied (anything hacky or suboptimal)\n   315→- Verification gaps (ACs that were hard to verify, weak evidence)\n   316→- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy)\n   317→If nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n   318→\n   319→MANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n   320→- Total tool calls: N\n   321→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n   322→- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n   323→- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n   324→- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls\"\n   325→  subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   326→```\n   327→\n   328→After the subagent returns:\n   329→1. Extract both `## Session Issues` and `## Token Report` sections and append to `.session-issues.md`\n   330→2. Parse the result: ALL_PASS → mark story `done`. PARTIAL → treat as failure (Step 3d-vii Path A).\n   331→3. **No Docker involved at any point.** Skip steps 3d-i through 3d-viii entirely.\n   332→\n   333→**runtime-provable verification (derived tier = runtime-provable):**\n   334→\n   335→Use a **single subagent** for the entire verification. Build the project, then run it locally — no Docker stack needed.\n   336→\n   337→```\n   338→Use the Agent tool with:\n   339→  prompt: \"Verify story {story_key} using local runtime checks (runtime-provable tier).\n   340→\n   341→Story file: _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/{story_key}.md\n   342→\n   343→Execute these steps and report results:\n   344→1. Run the project build command (npm run build, cargo build, etc). Report: PASS or FAIL + first 10 error lines.\n   345→2. Run tests (npm test, cargo test, etc). Report: PASS (N passed) or FAIL (N failed: list names).\n   346→3. Detect the project stack and determine the run command:\n   347→   - Node.js: npm start, or node dist/index.js, or npx ts-node src/index.ts\n   348→   - Rust: cargo run\n   349→   - Python: python -m app, or python main.py\n   350→   Check package.json scripts, Cargo.toml, or setup.py for clues.\n   351→4. Start the application in the background. Wait up to 10 seconds for it to be ready.\n   352→5. For each AC in the story file, verify it by interacting with the running app:\n   353→   - CLI apps: run with flags/args, check stdout/stderr/exit code\n   354→   - HTTP apps: curl localhost:{port}/endpoint, check response status and body\n   355→   - Check process behavior: signals, graceful shutdown, file output\n   356→   Report each AC as PASS or FAIL with one-line evidence.\n   357→6. Kill the running application process (kill PID or ctrl-C equivalent).\n   358→7. Generate proof document at verification/{story_key}-proof.md with evidence from each check.\n   359→8. Run codeharness verify --story {story_key} to validate the proof format.\n   360→9. Report final result: ALL_PASS (N/N ACs) or PARTIAL (M/N ACs, list failures).\n   361→\n   362→Do NOT use Docker. Do NOT run codeharness stack start. Do NOT start Docker containers.\n   363→Do NOT ask the user any questions. Do NOT run git commands. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n   364→\n   365→MANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n   366→- Problems encountered (build failures, app startup failures, port conflicts, timeouts)\n   367→- Workarounds applied (alternative run commands, fallback ports, manual process cleanup)\n   368→- Verification gaps (ACs that were hard to verify via runtime interaction, weak evidence)\n   369→- Observations (anything surprising about app behavior, startup time, resource usage)\n   370→If nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n   371→\n   372→MANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n   373→- Total tool calls: N\n   374→- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n   375→- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n   376→- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n   377→- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls\"\n   378→  subagent_type: \"general-purpose\"\n   379→```\n   380→\n   381→After the subagent returns:\n   382→1. Extract both `## Session Issues` and `## Token Report` sections and append to `.session-issues.md`\n   383→2. Parse the result: ALL_PASS → mark story `done`. PARTIAL → treat as failure (Step 3d-vii Path A).\n   384→3. **No Docker involved at any point.** Skip steps 3d-i through 3d-viii entirely.\n   385→\n   386→**escalate verification (derived tier = escalate):**\n   387→\n   388→When the derived tier is `escalate`, at least one AC requires human judgment or external services. Use mixed-tier dispatch:\n   389→\n   390→1. Re-read the story file. For each AC, extract its individual `<!-- verification: {tier} -->` tag (with legacy mapping as in Step 3d-0).\n   391→2. Group ACs by their individual tier:\n   392→   - `escalate`-tier ACs: mark each as `[ESCALATE]` in the proof document with the reason \"Requires human judgment or external service — cannot be automated.\"\n   393→   - All other ACs: dispatch verification at their individual tier level. Use the corresponding subagent prompt (test-provable, runtime-provable, or environment-provable) to verify those ACs specifically.\n   394→3. Generate proof document at `verification/{story_key}-proof.md`. Include:\n   395→   - PASS/FAIL verdict for each non-escalated AC (with evidence)\n   396→   - `[ESCALATE]` verdict for each escalated AC (with reason)\n   397→4. Run `codeharness verify --story {story_key}` to validate the proof format.\n   398→5. If all non-escalated ACs pass: mark story `done` with escalation notes. Print: `[WARN] Story {story_key} has {N} escalated ACs — marking done with known limitations`.\n   399→6. If any non-escalated AC fails: treat as failure (Step 3d-vii Path A).\n   400→7. If any non-escalated ACs were dispatched via the environment-provable path, run cleanup (step 3d-viii) to remove Docker containers and temp workspaces.\n   401→\n   402→**environment-provable verification (derived tier = environment-provable):** Full Docker container with no source code access.\n   403→\n   404→**No internal timeout.** Verification takes as long as it takes. Ralph's iteration timeout is the safety net.\n   405→\n   406→**Pre-verification: Read retry state from `ralph/.story_retries`.**\n   407→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01354VA1GpspSScsnH2wHagv","session_id":"f9b706e3-1764-4868-a4a5-c90b37d26d0d","uuid":"10d4d991-4da8-4cd3-98ec-256f2cd42122","timestamp":"2026-03-27T12:24:03.025Z"}
